{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2ee3464c-4658-4104-965e-ff9ffa8bcfb3","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the **`webapi`** template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n### Authentication options (`--auth`):\n\n| Value | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n### Example with auth:\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain mydomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` for custom token-based flows, or use ASP.NET Core Identity for local account management.\n\nWant me to scaffold a project with a specific auth configuration?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f0d64713-d647-43cf-8e06-3b41c867a154","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":277,"requestId":"A849:3ED17A:5CE8E50:65C0F2A:69F1564C"},"id":"d0379b85-7a31-4dc0-9d53-a7f63338ea56","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:52:36.431Z","parentId":"14c23f19-855e-4735-9b40-a3414ab23a8e"}
